By composing the extramural map $A_{\square}\to ^{\square}B$ (which is given on representatives by $\partial^{\text{ver}}$) with the intramural map $^{\square}B\to B^{\text{hor}}$ (which is the identity on coset representatives), we obtain a map $A_{\square}\to B^{\text{hor}}$. Composing *that* map with the intramural map $B^{\text{hor}}\to B_{\square}$, we obtain the 3-term sequence

$$A_{\square}\to B^{\text{hor}}\to B_{\square}.$$

For absolute clarity, we note that if $[a]\in A_{\square}$, then its image under the first map is $[\partial^{\text{vert}}(a)]\in B^{\text{hor}}$, and the image under the second map is $[\partial^{\text{vert}}(a)]\in B_{\square}$. The bracket notation for cosets is hiding the different *types* of cosets involved in these maps.

In any case, let's prove this sequence is exact at $B^{\text{hor}}$. First suppose an element $[b]\in B^{\text{hor}}$ is in the kernel of the intramural map $B^{\text{hor}}\to B_{\square}$. Recall that this intramural map is simply the identity on coset representatives, so we are now assuming the coset $[b]\in B_{\square}$ is the zero coset. By the definition of the [[40-49 Knowledge/41 Mathematics/Category theory/Abelian Categories/Double complexes and mural maps#^f322ef\|donor]], this implies $b$ is the sum of elements in the images of $\partial^{\text{vert}}$ and $\partial^{\text{hor}}$ mapping to $B$. In other words, there are elements $a\in A$ and $e\in E$ (where $E\to B$ is the map to the left of $B$) such that $b = \partial^{\text{vert}}(a)+\partial^{\text{hor}}(e)$.

Next, recall that we began with an element $[b]\in B^{\text{hor}}$. These coset representatives are only defined up to elements in the image of $E\to B$, so $[b]=[\partial^{\text{vert}}(a)]$.

Now notice that the element $b\in \ker(\partial^{\text{hor}})$, so applying $\partial^{\text{hor}}$ to the previous equation gives

$$0 = \partial^{\text{hor}}\partial^{\text{vert}}(a)+\partial^{\text{hor}}\partial^{\text{hor}}(e).$$

The last term on the right vanishes (since our diagram is part of a double-complex), so we can conclude $\partial^{\text{hor}}\partial^{\text{vert}}(a)=0$. In other words, $a\in \ker(\partial^{\text{diag}}_{\text{out}})$, and so $[a]\in A_{\square}$.

We've therefore proven $[b]\in B^{\text{hor}}$ is in the image of $A_{\square}\to B^{\text{hor}}$. So, we have shown that the kernel of $B^{\text{hor}}\to B_{\square}$ is contained in the image of $A_{\square}\to B^{\text{hor}}$.

Conversely, take any $[a]\in A_{\square}$. Then the image of $[a]$ under the map $A_{\square}\to B^{\text{hor}}$ is $[\partial^{\text{vert}}(a)]$. The element $\partial^{\text{vert}}(a)$ is (by definition!) in the image of $\partial^{\text{vert}}$ and hence is zero in the donor $B_{\square}$. Thus, the image of $A_{\square}\to B^{\text{hor}}$ is contained in the kernel of $B^{\text{hor}}\to B_{\square}$.

> [!question] Does this proof seem terrible to you?
> If you read through the above proof, you probably agree that it's terribly presented. I think this is a case in which "clever" notation is actually obscuring things and making "easy" proofs appear convoluted. Some day I will re-do this proof and attempt to make things more streamlined and clear.

# Extramural isomorphisms

Now let's see some corollaries of the Salamander Lemma. First let's focus on situations in which the mural maps are isomorphisms.

> [!summary] Extramural isomorphisms
> If for some horizontal arrow $\partial^{\text{hor}}:B\to C$ in the double complex one has $B^{\text{hor}}=0=C^{\text{hor}}$, then the horizontal extramural map $B_{\square}\nearrow \,^{\square}C$ is an isomorphism.
>
> Similarly, if for some vertical arrow $\partial^{\text{vert}}:B\to C$ in the double complex one has $B^{\text{vert}}=0=C^{\text{vert}}$, then the vertical extramural map
> 
> $$\begin{align*} B&_{\square}\\ \swarrow &\\ ^{\square}C \end{align*}$$
> 
> is an isomorphism.

The above is an immediate corollary of the corollary of the Salamander Lemma. For instance, the first statement follows from the exactness of the sequence below:

 $$A_{\square}\to 0\to B_{\square}\to ^{\square}C\to 0\to ^{\square}D.$$

Let's prove the above statement. First notice that we can extend the lower row to the left by inserting a zero object and arrow. Then, by our assumption, that bottom row is horizontally exact at $0$ and $B$:

$$0\to 0\to B\xrightarrow{f} C\to \cdots$$

By our extramural isomorphism them, we then have a horizontal isomorphism $0_{\square}\simeq ^{\square}B$. This proves $^{\square}B \simeq 0$, which we will use shortly.

By the Salamander Lemma, we have a six-term exact sequence

$$\bullet_{\square}\to 0^{\text{hor}}\to 0_{\square}\to ^{\square}A\to A^{\text{hor}}\to ^{\square}B.$$

Since $0_{\square}\simeq ^{\square}B \simeq 0$, the end of this exact sequence is the 4-term exact sequence

$$0\to ^{\square}A\to A^{\text{hor}}\to 0.$$

This proves $^{\square}A\simeq A^{\text{hor}}$.

By the Salamander Lemma, we have a six-term exact sequence

$$0_{\square}\to A^{\text{vert}}\to A_{\square}\to ^{\square}B\to B^{\text{vert}}\to ^{\square}\bullet.$$

Once again, since $0_{\square}\simeq ^{\square}B \simeq 0$, the beginning of this exact sequence is the 4-term exact sequence

$$0\to A^{\text{vert}}\to A_{\square}\to 0.$$

This proves $A^{\text{vert}}\simeq A_{\square}$.
